segments.text: I was born in Medina County in December the 8th, 1892.
I was born right on in a ranch house.
It's 25 miles from town.
What town?
Hondo.
Those days, well, I'd say every member of our family was born in that ranch house.
We was a family of 12 children.
Large family.
Very large family.
Could you tell us your dad's name?
Henry, Henry Rothery.
And your mother?
And her name was Anna Reinhardt.
She was coming from another old family of ours.
of German immigrant family and ranch people.
She comes from a large family.
She was very, she was very well adapted to ranch life.
Knew what it, and it was a hard, it was a hard life, you might say.
You know, when you,
when the mother takes care of a family of that size and together with oh I'd say we had we maintained probably a half a dozen ranch hands beside that and to cook and feed them do all that laundry.
That was a hard a hard life for a woman too.
It was but she was
I say she was well enough.
She was a very, very big woman.
Big frame, I mean, all muscle.
To maintain that, I mean, the schedule that she had to get up, oh, probably got up between four and five o'clock in the morning to start the day's program.
and breakfast food ready for the men that started out to work.
And they usually left the ranch house all daybreak.
And she lived to be, she died of a ruptured appendix when she was 78 years old.
She didn't know she was even bothered with it.
She'd been out.
She'd been out fishing with a sister of hers, and they had walked ten miles up and down the stream out there on the frill with a fish pole.
At 78.
That's marvelous.
She had a very strong constitution.
I think that's one of the things that's more so than my father.
My father was not...
He was a more of a, he was a pretty good horse trader.
And he proved it in his operations.
He was, he uh, I guess at one time had at least 50,000 acres in one tract of land in Medina County and 20,000 acres more out there.
Oh, in Brackettville, I believe.
That's...
I think it's Emmett County, I'm not sure, but it's around out there, and it was in that county of Brackettville.
And he left all his children pretty well set up.
He left his old $50,000 piece.
That's the closest I'd hold that on.
Well, it's been a long time.
Can you tell us a little bit about your boyhood, your experiences?
Yes.
He moved us, of course, he moved the family to San Antonio.
Like I say, he was strongly interested in education.
And so we could go to school.
And he moved, that was the first time that I ever saw a train was about in 1895 when
We drove down from that ranch to get on that train to go to San Antonio.
Must have been quite an experience.
It was, I'll tell you.
I know we got to San Antonio.
We lived there in San Antonio then until about 19, until 1905 or 6 or 7, along in there.
At that time, Hondo had, it had developed the way that they voted out.
a school district and build a pretty good schoolhouse, and he thought it would be more convenient to move the family back to Hondo, closer to his place, to where he was in business.
He was, of course, spending quite a bit of his time then in Hondo itself.
He was president of the bank there.
He had tried
operating a big mercantile business, which didn't turn out too successfully as he was too trustful.

He didn't even watch his business and they turned it over to a friend and they left him about $120,000 in the red when his creditors came in and wanted to know what he was going to do about his business.

in hondo well i finished the public schools and then attended a preparatory school in san antonio for a year before i went to a m and had an a m in 19 in the fall of 1911. why did you go to a m why did you pick that school well i imagine i'd had um three other brothers there before me and i think my father of course

as he is associated, I might say his life work was associated with his cattle and agriculture, that he was interested more in his children going to the school of an agricultural school than Texas University.
He had no use.
I remember some of the boys said they probably
want to go to Austin to study law, Texas University.
He says you go to A&M or study some form of engineering.
I had a brother then that he went to Michigan School of Mines and another brother went to Ohio State and studied veterinary science.
Now, when did you enter Anaheim?
In the fall of when?
My first year down there was the year they started.
They had the idea of, I don't know, they burned down all the old buildings.
Something happened, yes.
You heard that story, I guess.
Well, I knew they burned, but I don't know about the story of it.
Well, I don't know it either, but then the fact that so many of them burned up, it's...
Unusual.
It almost got the idea that somebody was mixed up with it.
They burned up the old mess hall, the one they called the old original Speeder mess hall.
Then they burned up the main building, which brought the school, I'd say, to a stop, because most of the classrooms were in the main building.
And they disrupted, of course, burning up the missile.
They suspended school for 30 days and in the meantime put up a temporary missile, built it out there out of sheet iron.
Oh, I don't believe they had a concrete floor.
I believe they just put in a plain old floor in there and a sheet iron side and roof on it.
Wooden floor.
Yeah, wooden floor.
And they used that building then until they built the, I guess, the old, the present mess hall is still in use, isn't it?
Visa Hall is still in use, yes.
Where did you live that first year?
I, my first year in school, I was in Foster Hall.
at one of the old dormitories.
My last GI, they gave me a company captainship and put me over there in Milner.
Uh-huh, and still there.
Still there.
Milner's still there.
Foster Hall's gone.
And I think George Crawford was in my company.
Yes, I believe he was.
What other recollections do you have of that first year on the campus there?
How did the school impress you?
What was it like?
Oh, well, of course it was so different from anything I had ever come in contact with.
The first thing that was a, we were entering the
the football season.
And there was one form of hazing that they had there.
They'd bring out all the fish.
They'd assemble all the fish and put them in nightshade.
And that was the days before pajamas.
put on their nightshades and frayed them around all over the campus.
We'd go all up and down where the professors would live in what they called Quality Row.
Does it still go by that name?
Oh, it's gone, but I've got pictures of it.
No, it's been torn down.
Yeah, we had those pep rallies.
Went on for quite frequently.
I'd say that we had a pep rally at, oh, two or three every week.
They call them yell practices now.
Do they call them yell practices?
Yell practice, yes.
Yes.
And yell leaders.
Right, we still have them.
No girls.
No girls in the yell leaders.
And you went there in 1911.
And that was one of the things that impressed me about our year leader.
He was an old boy from Millinder.
And he come out of way out of the Morpha.
Morpha or West of Morpha.
And he was a
almost every week for non-regulation uniform because he wouldn't wear anything but boots with his trousers stuck to the top of his boots.
Do you remember his name?
Yeah, Milliner.
Milliner?
Yeah.
Lindy.
Lindy Milliner.
Milliner.
Okay.
I met him through World War I. I ran across him over there in France.
He was a captain.
I was his chaplain.
And you said you went there in 1911?
Mm-hmm.
When did you graduate?
The 17th.
So you must have had some time off.
Yes, they gave me time off.
Because, you know, the old hazing, it was pretty much, it was practiced pretty heavily in those days.
And you had, those were the days when they had no heat except stoves.
And there was no...
the water, you got your water from a hydrant outside.
And all them sophomores and upperclassmen, the fish had to always go out and keep their wood box filled up and keep their water bucket full.
And if you didn't, if you was a sophomore's fish and he come up there and there was no wood there, boy, you was in a
in trouble.
I was, from my early training, I was, I guess in the habit of keeping myself pretty neat.
You had to take care of your own uniform.
You got yourself
You only had the old cadet grays at that time.
There was no khakis.
And you had to keep them trousers pressed pretty good if you wanted to look good.
We did guard duty.
I don't think they do that anymore.
No, not much.
But all the guard duty was, the cadets had
had to do three, what they call, three tours of guard duty at night.
It went on from 7 to 10 o'clock, and that was the study period.
And during that study period, there was supposed to be a sentry in that dormitory, in that hall, just walking round and round.
And I remember my first night, I came on sentry duty.
I was in the legate, and there was a bunch of football players in there.
And somebody stuck his head out and said, uh-oh, got a fish on sentry tonight.
And they almost tore that dormitory to pieces.
They run all over me because I was a fish, you know.
And then up comes up.
And the cadet major, I'll never forget that bird, he almost got me canned.
Oh, I tell you, man, he'd come up there and yank me up.
You want to know what I meant by letting all this disturbance going on on my post?
Why, I didn't stop him.
I said, I can't do nothing with them big football players.
He says, you're on charge.
You got your gun, your bayonet.
He said, just take after them.
Get them out of there.
And then he made me go through all my general orders and my special orders.
I knew all that stuff.
And then his final

instruction when he left me says I want you to report yourself to the guardhouse when you're going on for for allowing this disturbance so when I got off I went into the to the sergeant of the guard and made my report he says yay sergeant of guard says
The majors already beat you to it.
And that was an unusual coincidence that got me off of the hook on that deal.
The brother that went to Ohio State was coming home one summer and in the Pullman with him,
was a young lieutenant out of West Point who was reporting to A&M as a commander.
And my brother was telling him that he had a younger brother who was going to A&M that fall.
And so when I, we call that the RAM list for any misdemeanor.
I don't know whether they still have a misdemeanor list or not.
But every night,
Every night at supper, the adjutant would read out the RAM list.
And then it would be a list of 150 names at least.
Every night.
And there was my name on there that night for... And I got the maximum amount of demerits.
How many was that?
I think it was five on one offense.
Five demerits.
And I...
and with instructions to report to the, to the commandant.
Well, I walk into the commandant's office, told him my name, and he says, yes, he says, I know you.
He says, you know, I had a nice visit with your brother.
He says, we came, I came down here riding on the Pullman with him, and he, he told me about his early experiences at A&M and that
that he had a younger brother, and you were him, the younger brother of the man I met, and I said, yes.
And we talked on a little bit, and he was telling me how much he enjoyed.
He said, I'll tell you what you do, he says,
Just write an explanation to me about that and I'll take care of it.
And boy, I wrote my explanation and he scratched off the demerits of me.
Because if there's one thing, I'll say, that my father wasn't put up with, and that was disobedience.
And I knew how that was going to stand in my quarter
You see, we had two terms at that time.
We had two terms, and my report home with those demerits on it, and I was working my head off to get those demerits off me, so when my report goes home, no demerit.
And that's what I meant about that I had acquired the habit of keeping myself in sort of a spit and polish condition.
When I turned out to guard my office,

When you went up to Gordon in those days, the adjutant would inspect you, and after he looked through, you know, inspect your rifle, your general appearance and everything, and he'd pick out the cadet that had the neatest appearance, and for that he got five demerit credits,
and excused from walking a post.
And that's one of the things that got me into trouble in a way.
Because I used to have to, for the sophomores, that when they got on guard duty, they'd come down and say, say, Fish, I'm on guard mount this morning.
He said, get yourself all fixed up and go on out there to guard mount and come back with them five points of credit for me.
And I'd go out to the guard mount and then get around.
If I got the credit to ask me what my name, I'd give the name of their sophomore.
That agent says, how many names you got?
That's good.
That's really good.
Now, you left A&M for a while.
Oh, yeah.
Next year, I come back.
Of course, I was a bigot.
And I got deported on a fish.
And we made the mistake, one of the fish in the company that was in the old Ann Foster Hall was the son of a state senator.
And when he went home at Christmas, he complained to his father about the terrible treatment that he was subjected to down in that hazing.
And the senator,
came back to Austin and reported it to the governor.
And the governor wrote the president a letter of the conditions that was going down there and ordered an explanation and for him to check into it and make a report.
And one day, in about the first, it was either the first or the second week after January when it got back,
why the company, our company commander, I think, as I remember, his name was Oliver.
He says, no, it wasn't him.
It was the old bull himself.
They called the...
the commandant, the bull in those days.
Still called military, regular military bulls.
Well, the old commandant, he'd come out there and he said, and he read off these names and he said, I read these names, you will step one pace forward.
Well, as was a custom in those days, the fish all had the rear rank,
and the upperclassmen had the front rank.
And when he got through calling the names, the front rank had stepped one piece forward.
And he said, you men whose names I've called will be excused from drill, but you will put your guns and bayonets away and report to the disciplining committee in one hour.
And he was, he was, he had a wonderful memory for names.
I only appeared before him when I reported back in, I mean, at the first school.
And there was a new commandant there, the one I was talking about the first.
He had been assigned to another,
tour of duty somewhere else.
And this fellow's name was Levi G. Brown.
I always remember that name because when they read the land list, the ram list, it says, by order of Levi G. Brown, Commandant.
And Levi...
When I walked up before the district committee, he just called my name out.
Brother H.H.
He didn't ask me what my name was.
He called me.
And he said, you've been accused by cadet so-and-so, and he named the son of the senator, for taking part in a hazing incident just before Christmas.
And he says, are you guilty or not guilty?
I said, I'm guilty.
That's all.
And we were all expelled.
My goodness.
And that's when the cadet corps went on a strike.
All 27, there was 27 of us, got canned out of there.
Well, they didn't say how long a time we just came.
We were reinstated.
the following, during the summer sometime, and I went back in the summer.
So I came back, I started taking architecture.
That was my architectural engineering.
And I came back, and when I walked into that commandant's office,
I just stuck my head in the door, and there was old Brown sitting over there, and he looked up and he says, Rory, I'm glad to see you back.
He didn't hesitate a moment.
That's why I say he had a marvelous memory for names.
You said there was a strike.
Do you know anything about that strike, what went on then?
Well, it was dissolved.
in just what way, and all the cadets that would come back, there were no charges filed against them.
But you left, you weren't there during the strike.
Oh no, I had to leave.
I mean, we were told to leave and get off that campus before 12 o'clock that night.
Right, goodness.
And we left there, and we caught, there was a night train left there just about 11 o'clock, and we caught that
How many got expelled along with you?
How many was there?
Twenty-seven.
Are they all sophomores?
Sophomores and juniors.
What incident provoked this?
That hazing.
What did y'all do that was so bad and got you kicked out?
Well, just give them a good strapping.
Before you went home Christmas, that was our Christmas present.
We lined up all the fish.
It was a general practice.
Just before you go home Christmas,
All the upperclassmen would line you up and they'd all take a whack at your rear end with a belt.
And so this boy thought he had a little too much.
Well, yeah, and he was a son of a senator.
Oh, I see.
Well, that shouldn't have made him too popular.
No, he'd never come back.
Oh, my goodness.
So you had to lay out then for that second semester in the summer then.
And then I sort of lost my contact.
Well, I didn't lose it too bad, but I was a pretty fair student.
But I was taking part and I was a pretty fair track man.
I'll just put it that way.
I had one time I held a record in the broad jump in the pole vault for the state.
I didn't know that.
What year did you hold that record?
Well, I set it in 15, and it was broken by an A&M man in 1919.
That must have been quite an honor to hold that.
Well, I thought it was.
But I just had another incident about this fellow Bull Brown.
I was, I came down here, down here to the valley and the American Legion post had an idea, you know, they come, we'll make us a war picture and make us some money.
And we didn't have no equipment.
And Ringgold, that's an army post right up here in Rio Grande City.
It's up about, it's about 25, 30 miles up there, right up the river road.
And another fellow was put on, we'd had some contact with Ringgold up there.
Well, we put on a committee to go up there and see him, but if we could borrow some uniforms,
and some army equipment, rifles and something, to make this picture with.
And we didn't think his name.
And we walked into the Adjutant's office.
We both knew him.
There was a fellow with me.
He was a veterinarian and a doctor here by the name of Ootsman.
And we walked in there and we was talking to this Adjutant.
And the Adjutant says,
We told him what our mission was, that we wanted to borrow some uniform and maybe some ordnance, rifles and stuff like that.
We had a plan of making a picture down there, a movie picture.
One of these promoters come along, you know how they do, come into a small town and try to promote something to make some money on.
And he sold us on this idea of making this movie.
Well,
He says, the agent says to us, he says, you know, this place has just turned, had a turnover of commanding officers.
And the new commanding officer, he just got here yesterday.
And he said, there's his office.
He said, I can't say I don't know him too well.
He said, I've been here a day.
He said, I'm sure he'd be cooperative just going in, just tell him what your deal is.
I think he'd help out now.
I looked around like that, we both looked around, and there was Bo Brown.
He said, Rory, come on in here.
I want to talk to you.
When was this?
When did you do it?
When was this?
What date?
Do you remember what year?
It was about 25.
And the last time I saw him was probably about 1914, before that.
And in 1925, I went in there and we had a nice boat session with the old colonel.
He was a colonel by that time.
And he was the highest ranking American officer captured in World War I. I'll be darned.
And I run into, I said I operated the Bibian, the tavern dealer there for a while.
And I met an old boy, World War I boy, and he had quite an experience.
He was with the...
I thought I'd remember his division.
And he and his colonel got along very well.
He said, you know, he was telling me about his colonel, how well...
how well his colonel thought of him, that he could get anything he wanted out of his colonel, because the colonel said I was the best army sergeant he'd ever had.
And he said, I can't think of his name, but you know he was the highest American army officer, kept you doing well going?
And I said, you don't know his name?
I said, I know him very well.
He said, what do you know about him?
He said, you wasn't in our outfit.
I said, no, but I know the guy you're talking about.
And I said, not much, his name was Levi G. Brown.
He said, that's what it was.
Now, you were involved in a very interesting incident
involving the branding of the Texas Longhorn.
Could you tell us how that took place leading up to that?
Who was involved and how y'all went about it?
Well, I'll tell you, one of the things that promoted it, did you ever, you heard of the incident at the time when they got Rice's Owl, did you?
No, I don't have it.
Well, that happened just before that.
The basketball team went down to play Rice, and they played that.
In those days, you know, you had very limited facilities.
And Rice did not have a gym.
And we just had a makeshift gym.
And they played in the YMCA gym downtown.
And Rice comes down.
Do they still have that old stuffed owl?
I believe so.
They used to have a stuffed owl.
It was about a six-foot deal.
Painted up, you know, like an owl.
And that was their mascot.
And they'd bring it out to all their athletic contests and set it on the sideline.
And they brought it down there for that basketball game.
And when the game was over,
where they carelessly left that owl sat in there somewhere.

And that A&M basketball team, when they got through dressing and cleaning up, and they come out and they saw that owl sat in there, they thought, well, I think we'll just take him back to college with us.
They just picked it up, brought it down there, and put it in the express car.
brought it on up to College Station.
Well, they had a lot of fun with it around a couple of days.
They paraded that aisle around there.
Brazell was president at that time, and they brought it over there to Brazell's residence.
He'd come out and had his picture made with it.
They published it in the Houston papers, and it got them Ross aisle boys kind of stirred up, and they made a deal with a private eye to come up and
And so I surveyed the deal and find out where we kept the owl and what was done with it.
And he come up there and posed as a sports writer for one of the newspapers.
And the boys, the basketball players or whoever it was, took him up.
We kept him up in the arm.
He was up on the fourth floor.
main building of the old or it was of course a new main building at that time.

So they took him up there and showed him why the aisle and and brought him out and he made some pictures of it and that night he after he got through he said I'm going to write you all boys up a good story on this deal.
He wired down to those rice
cadets that had it all spotted up for them to come up that night.
They came up in a car.
And they came up there right around midnight.
And they went up there and broke into the armory.
And the night watchman discovered the deal and fired off a volley of shots or something.
And it was right around 12 o'clock at night.
And boy, everybody tumbled out of bed in just no time at all.
The word got around that a bunch of rice cadets came up and got that owl out of the army.
And just about that time, one of them passenger trains was going south, and everybody tore off for the depot.

I went down and just commandeered that train and about two or three hundred cadets, at least two or three hundred cadets swarmed on top of that thing and told them to take off and went on down the road toward Dunn.
What's the name of that town just south of College?
Hempstead?
No, no, a little closer.
Just south of College Station there.
About 20.
Welborn?
About 20 miles south of it.
Pretty concise town at that time.
Well, anyhow, they didn't get very far.
I wasn't on the deal.
But they didn't get very far.
And right in those days, just what they called a highway was just a little old dirt road running along the railroad track.
There they saw them.
Saw those rice hounds with that
with that owl in the cart.
And they run on about a half a mile and pull that string and stop the train.
Everybody went out, towed a barricade across the road.
And towed, and run those cadets all over that Bradford's Bottom down there.
They finally picked them all up.
turned their car around just before they picked him up while the Rice Isles, those Rice Isles set fire to their mascot and burned him up.
They brought him back up to College Station and walked him around there for about two days until, and then the president of Rice called Dr. Bezell and said,
There's enough of that horseplay going around to have those harassed students turned loose and let them come back and go to school.
Well, old Doc Giselle complied with the request.
He turned them loose.
But that sports writer, he was in a bad way.
They finally found out who he was, that he was a private eye, and they brought him back.
And they turned him over to the fish, and them fish really mistreated him, something terrible.
They walked him around, just walked him around, and just kept threatening him all the time.
And he was just pleading all the time for his life.
He thought he was going to get killed.
And they finally told him, said, we're going to turn you loose.
Some of the upperclassmen told them to turn him loose.
And they took him out on the parade ground, and it was a cold night.
It was freezing or better.
Took him out there on the parade ground at midnight, undressed him, took all his clothes off, gave him his shoes, and said, all right, go on to Houston if you want to.
And that's what
And that's what led us up to the, we kind of got it into our system, you know, about playing pranks.
And Texas University was getting a lot of publicity about their mascot.
They didn't have any name for him.
They didn't have any name.
No, up to that time they had no name, but he was a marvelous specimen of a lawnmower.
of a big, raw, just a big-boned, mean outlaw.
I've had the experience with them.
I spent all my boyhood on a ranch, and I know what they are.
When they brought them out for a football game, they had four men on horseback with ropes on them in every direction.
one on each side, and they'd lead him up and down the football field because, I mean, one rope, he'd take after him.
You had to have him tied from every direction to take care of him.
And they was putting on all this big deal about, they have a sort of a homecoming or the letterman,
on Texas Independence Day.
And they had won that game that year by a score of, I think it was 20 to three or some such score as that.
Just the year before that, we beat Texas
13 to nothing.
And you know Texas and A&M quit playing football there for a period of time.
You've heard the name Charlie Moran.
Well Charlie Moran was a guy that brought, he brought in the recruiting idea really into Texas schools.
Charlie was an old pro.
He was a pro football player and a pro
baseball player, and of course he had played college football as a youngster.
But when he came to A&M, it was just at the time when, right shortly after the Congress had suspended athletics
all athletics at Carlisle University in Pennsylvania, that old Indian school, the one that Jim Thorpe went to.
Well, there were a bunch of pretty good football players on the loose around that, and Charlie got hold of about three of them, of the old Carlisle football players.
And he brought in several others.
He had quite a football player brought in from Alabama, and he got one out of Colorado, Lyman.
200-pound men in those days was unusual, and these were around 225, 230-pound boys.
Could we stop just a minute and let me turn my tape over?
I'm running out on this side.
Okay.
Thank you.
